    <section class="row">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>Students use unit fractions to compose and decompose fractions with relational rods. Using different rods to represent the whole, students are asked to name the unit fractions they can find.</p>

      <h4>Mathematics</h4>
      <p>This task encourages students to think flexibly about the concept of a whole, recognizing that a whole can be any length, and that when representing fractions visually (e.g., on a number line or in an area model) each partition must be of
        equal size. </p>

      <h4>Curriculum Connections</h4>
      <p>Students will:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>determine, through investigation, the relationships among fractions</li>
        <li>divide whole objects into equal parts and identify the equal parts using fractional names.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="row">
      <h4>Instructional Sequence</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>Give each student a set of relational rods. Tell students to take out one of the orange rods. Inform them that one orange rod represents one whole.</li>
        <li>Ask students to:
          <ol type="a">
            <li>use different rods of the same colour to build a whole, which is equivalent to the orange</li>
            <li>name the unit fractions of the new wholes they created (i.e., 10 one-tenths, 5 one-fifths, or 2 one-halves).</li>
          </ol>
        </li>
        <li>Reinforce with students that when the orange rod is the whole, they should be able to represent and name halves (yellow), fifths (red) and tenths (white).</li>
        <li>Repeat steps 1 through 3 using the blue rod as the whole.</li>
        <li>Repeat with other rods as the whole to consolidate student thinking and encourage flexibility with wholes and units.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="row">
      <div class="col-sm-6 col-md-6 no-padding-left">
        <h4>Highlights of Student Thinking</h4>
        <p>Students may:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>wonder what to do when rods show more than the whole</li>
          <li>identify fractions that canâ€™t be constructed by the relational rods (e.g., no rods show thirds with orange as whole)</li>
          <li>try to use multiple colours to compare to the whole</li>
          <li>use whole numbers (e.g., 1, 2, 3... and to count unit fractions rather than attending to the unit of 1 one-fifth, 2 one-fifths...)</li>
          <li>explore other wholes and related unit fractions intuitively</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="col-sm-6 col-md-6 no-padding-left">
        <h4 class="title-indentation">Key Questions</h4>
        <ol>
          <li>Which rods can <em>only</em> and be composed using all white rods?</li>
          <li>Why does the white rod represent <abbr title="one tenth" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>10</sub></span></abbr> when orange is the whole, but <abbr title="one nineth" class="abbr-frac"><span
                class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>9</sub></span></abbr> when blue is the whole? How does the whole change the names of the unit fractions?</li>
          <li>If blue represents 1 whole, what do 4 green rods represent?</li>
          <li>When is purple <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr> compared to the whole? Is <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr>
            always the same size with different length wholes?</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </section>

